• New approach to detect duplicated subjects in multi-camera monitoring;
• By combining classification and regression methods, fewer subject-specific details are required, eliminating
the need for high-quality recordings or complex models to perform face recognition;
• Our contribution is suitable for resource-constrained devices, such as those used in edge computing.

Algorithm 1 Semi-supervised Field-of-View (FOV) Delimiter Estimation
Input: Synchronized video streams captured by camera objects s1, s2
Output: Estimated FOV delimiter lines for each camera
Data:
s1: Camera 1
s2: Camera 2
1 detections.s1 ← empty list;
2 detections.s2 ← empty list;
3 foreach synchronized frame pair (f1, f2) from (s1, s2) do
4 | faces.s1 ← YOLOv11(f1);
5 | faces.s2 ← YOLOv11(f2);
6 foreach face entering s2 through red edge do
7 | candidates.s1 ← MovingFaces(faces.s1);
8 | j ← length(candidates.s1);
9 | foreach candidate in candidates.s1 do
10 | | detections.s1.append((candidate.coordinates, 1/j));
11 | end
12 | end
13 foreach face entering s1 through red edge do
14 | candidates.s2 ← MovingFaces(faces.s2);
15 | j ← length(candidates.s2);
16 foreach candidate in candidates.s2 do
17 | | detections.s2.append((candidate.coordinates, 1/j));
18 | end
19 | end
20 end
21 FOV.line.s1 ← wRANSAC(detections.s1);
22 FOV.line.s2 ← wRANSAC(detections.s2);
23 return FOV.line.s1, FOV.line.s2
